            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "I found this bug only happened if new float window is larger than old one (fzf term win). So the `math.random`(in above repro) can be replace with larger number than fzf's height/width.\n\nHere's something looks suspicious:\n`nvim_open_win` will first do `win_new_float`, then `win_set_buf`. But in `win_new_float`, it first reuse a `oldp->w_buffer` (in `win_init`) https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/703f4037c475ee504b71d393e152fb1ae44c7bb9/src/nvim/window.c#L1572\n\nThen in `terminal_check_size` (which trigger \"reflow\") try to find the largest window point to current terminal instance https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/05b9daa1e6e8d045f691b74441ebbc01f69a56aa/src/nvim/terminal.c#L660\n```\n→ terminal_check_size(Terminal * term):662\n  win_set_inner_size(win_T * wp, _Bool valid_cursor):6680\n  win_config_float(win_T * wp, WinConfig fconfig):228\n  win_new_float(win_T * wp, _Bool last, WinConfig fconfig, Error * err):114\n```\n\nBut at this moment, for new created float win, this is always true. So when its size is larger, reflow maybe happen?",
